ategory>风险新闻</category><category>助学贷款</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>职业教育</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Biden, Netanyahu and the Anti-Israel Democrats]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统在会见以色列总理时改变了主意。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096182615853368"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096182615853368"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 6:37 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-israel-isaac-herzog-benjamin-netanyahu-democrats-pramila-jayapal-62b00e15"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819563?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，乔·拜登总统（右）在华盛顿白宫椭圆形办公室会见以色列总统艾萨克·赫尔佐格。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Shawn Thew/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周五，这些专栏<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-israel-benjamin-netanyahu-tom-nides-iran-abraham-accords-judicial-reform-639bd846?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">批评</a>拜登总统冷落以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡，以无端的公开方式拒绝邀请他访问白宫。周一，总统改变了主意，致电耶路撒冷并计划今年举行会晤。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这会是一场盛大而仪式的白宫会议，还是在联合国间隙举行的快速 30 场会议？这应该不重要，除非拜登政府似乎认为这很重要，拒绝了以色列的要求。这个逻辑不难解读：内塔尼亚胡先生希望向选民保证，他一直保持着牢固的美以关系，而拜登先生不想让他这么做。</p><p>本周艾萨克·赫尔佐格所受到的待遇充分说明了这一点。赫尔佐格先生曾是内塔尼亚胡的反对者，现在担任以色列总统，担任非政治角色。他周二在白宫会见了拜登，并于周三在国会联席会议上发表讲话。为了他，拜登政府铺开了内塔尼亚胡先生拒绝的红地毯。</p><p>向以色列人传达的信息是，美国与你们站在一起，但不与你们的政府站在一起。这是我们告诉古巴人和伊朗人的事情，或者至少我们过去是这样告诉的。白宫对盟友民主采取同样的做法是民主党的时代标志。</p><p>上周，白宫发表声明，敦促以色列“保护和尊重司法改革抗议者的和平集会权利”——就好像以色列做了其他事情一样。纽约众议员杰里·纳德勒称以色列的改革提案“反民主”，并对司法独立构成威胁。他和其他民主党人支持重组美国最高法院，并将其置于国会的回避规则之下，这似乎从未引发任何认知失调。他们将以色列视为一个初期的独裁国家。</p><p>周六，进步核心小组主席、西雅图众议员普拉米拉·贾亚帕尔 (Pramila Jayapal) 在 Netroots Nation 活动家会议上表示，“我想让你们知道，我们一直在努力表明以色列是一个种族主义国家。”这种错误的说法是苏联宣传的主要内容，其道德倒错是显而易见的。以色列是中东地区种族主义最少的国家，与巴勒斯坦权力机构形成鲜明对比。</p><p>贾亚帕尔女士在亲巴勒斯坦抗议者质问伊利诺伊州众议员扬·沙科夫斯基（Jan Schakowsky）后发表了讲话。沙科夫斯基本人经常批评以色列，但恰好是犹太人。</p><p>共和党人正在提出一项决议，称以色列不是一个“种族主义或种族隔离国家”，但这次轻松的投票将使大多数民主党人摆脱困境。众议院民主党领导人拒绝了贾亚帕尔女士的说法，认为“政府官员来来去去。美国和以色列之间的特殊关系将持续下去。”</p><p>贾亚帕尔女士表示，她被视为有色人种女性。她还试图澄清：“我不认为以色列作为一个国家的观念是种族主义的。然而，我确实相信内塔尼亚胡的极右翼政府实施了歧视性和公然的种族主义政策。”对于她的不撤回，以色列主要自由主义游说团体 J Street 为她辩护。贾亚帕尔女士和其他常见嫌疑人甚至会抵制赫尔佐格总统的演讲。</p><p>自由派在措辞上争论不休——你应该说“民主”和“内塔尼亚胡”，而不是“种族主义”和“犹太复国主义”——但在总统口角和司法改革的掩护下，对以色列的诽谤已经成为主流。民主党。即使以色列有了新总理，这也很难挽回。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=87D9068E-77D8-4079-9F23-679C8A6B3081&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbiden-israel-isaac-herzog-benjamin-netanyahu-democrats-pramila-jayapal-62b00e15&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">经过一场强调军事优先事项与文化问题的辩论后，众议院共和党人于 7 月 14 日通过了《国防授权法案》(NDAA)。图片：Getty Images 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-israel-isaac-herzog-benjamin-netanyahu-democrats-pramila-jayapal-62b00e15</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-israel-isaac-herzog-benjamin-netanyahu-democrats-pramila-jayapal-62b00e15<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Countering Russia’s Grain Deal Extortion]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果普京实施封锁，可能需要海军护航行动。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590095503536146356"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590095503536146356"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 6:35 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sea-grain-initiative-vladimir-putin-russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelensky-f17649e0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819600?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，乌克兰敖德萨，火箭碎片落在一栋私人建筑的屋顶上，工人们从屋顶上的一个洞中取出火箭的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：igor tkachenko/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>希望解除制裁，他再次威胁全球粮食供应以实现这一目标。周一，俄罗斯退出了促进乌克兰粮食出口的黑海粮食倡议。普京周二对乌克兰粮食出口港敖德萨发动导弹袭击。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>据世界粮食计划署称，战前乌克兰农场养活了全世界约 4 亿人。去年夏天，在土耳其和联合国的斡旋下，黑海粮食倡议允许约 3200 万吨小麦、玉米和其他农作物从乌克兰港口起运，尽管当时正发生战争。</p><p>该协议还意味着约 45 个国家可以继续获得乌克兰粮食。其中包括土耳其、埃及和突尼斯等粮食通胀高企的国家，以及阿富汗、索马里、苏丹和也门等面临粮食短缺的国家。联合国估计，黑海谷物倡议“自 2022 年 3 月以来已帮助将粮食价格降低了 23% 以上”。乌克兰可以使用欧洲的陆路进行部分出口，但不能达到航运允许的数量。</p><p>克里姆林宫在这一脆弱性中看到了政治影响力。普京<a href="https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2023/07/13/not-one-russian-demand-of-ukraine-grain-deal-fulfilled-putin-a81836" target="_blank" class="icon none">称</a>上周的这一举措“完全是片面的”，并声称“没有采取任何行动，根本没有采取任何行动”来满足俄罗斯的要求。</p><p>但根据一项<a href="https://news.un.org/pages/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/MOU_21_July_UN-Secretariat86.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">平行协议，</a>联合国同意与克里姆林宫合作，“促进俄罗斯食品和化肥不受阻碍地进入全球市场”。联合国<a href="https://www.ft.com/content/c10bcdb9-d01d-4a01-a4a1-38736e263a1e" target="_blank" class="icon none">数据</a>显示，2022年前10个月，俄罗斯化肥出口增长70%，达到167亿美元，联合国秘书长安东尼奥·古特雷斯最近<a href="https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/sg/press-encounter/2023-07-17/secretary-generals-press-encounter-the-black-sea-initiative" target="_blank" class="icon none">指出</a>，“俄罗斯粮食贸易已达到很高的出口量”。</p><p>周一，乌克兰总统泽连斯基<a href="https://kyivindependent.com/zelensky-on-black-sea-grain-deal-collapse-we-are-not-afraid/" target="_blank" class="icon none">表示，</a> “我们并不害怕”，“即使没有俄罗斯联邦，我们也必须尽一切努力，以便我们能够使用这条黑海走廊。”他值得西方的支持。</p><p>去年秋天，当俄罗斯短暂暂停参与粮食倡议时，乌克兰、土耳其和联合国仍继续推进了运输计划。克里姆林宫最终重新加入了该协议，值得再次揭穿克里姆林宫的虚张声势。</p><p>俄罗斯希望国有的俄罗斯农业银行能够重新使用促进跨境支付的 Swift 系统，以及西方的其他让步。但这将在制裁方面造成相当大的漏洞。更重要的是，普京先生将了解到，它正在劫持世界粮食供应。</p><p>普京无所不能，但如果他动用军事力量实施食品封锁，他就会冒相当大的风险。美国和全世界应该让他知道，如果他这样做，结果将是在黑海进行海军护航行动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=19149F3B-99F4-448C-946E-EFE2715F4553&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fblack-sea-grain-initiative-vladimir-putin-russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelensky-f17649e0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：随着美国宣布集束炸弹将被纳入其对乌克兰的 8 亿美元军事援助计划中，复兴的北约来到维尔纽斯，但未来的领导层充满了不确定性。图片：美联社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:35:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sea-grain-initiative-vladimir-putin- Russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelensky-f17649e0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sea-grain-initiative-vladimir-putin- Russia-ukraine-volodymyr-zelensky-f17649e0<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>农业</category><category>农业</category><category>油籽/谷物种植</category><category>玉米种植</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>勒索/勒索</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黑海谷物倡议</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>勒索</category><category>勒索</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>农业</category><category>农业</category><category>油籽</category><category>粮食种植</category><category>玉米种植</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Of EVs and Heat Waves]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>为了帮助应对气候变化，请将您的特斯拉磨成小颗粒并将其注入大气中。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590095652141982236"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590095652141982236"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">小</span><span class="author" itemprop="name">霍尔曼·W·詹金斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 6:32 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819088?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6 月 22 日，特斯拉电动汽车在加利福尼亚州霍桑市的一个充电站充电。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Caroline Brehman/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一个故事正在流传。消费者对里程的焦虑是电动汽车销量增加的绊脚石，也是汽车制造商被迫推出大尺寸电动汽车的原因，因为电池太大，以至于达不到减排的目的。</p><p>调查显示，里程焦虑确实是消费者的一大困扰。但这甚至还没有触及我们的电动汽车政策中问题的表面——有人可能会说，这是疯狂的。</p><p>如果目标是减少排放，世界将征收碳税。那么我们会得到什么样的电动汽车呢？不是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>，而是像<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TM" class="">丰</a>田普锐<span class="company-name-type">斯</span>这样的混合动力汽车。 “一辆装满稀土和锂的独轮车可以为一辆[电池驱动的汽车]或超过 90 辆混合动力车提供动力，但是，呃，政策制定者似乎忽视了这一事实，”一位加州经销商最近给我发了一封电子邮件。</p><p>他的数字显然源自丰田，在绿色游说界掀起了一股小<a href="https://cleantechnica.com/2023/07/17/the-hybrid-plug-in-hybrid-electric-car-debate-rages-on/" target="_blank" class="icon none">骚动</a>。理论上，一辆特斯拉中使用的相同电池矿物如果分布在一组普锐斯上，可以减少 37 倍的排放量。</p><p>这只会让那些没有注意到的人感到震惊。政府当然不会忽视这一点。俄亥俄州立大学可持续交通专家克里斯·阿特金森（Chris Atkinson）是奥巴马能源部的一位重要官员，我之前曾引用过他的口号——“电池的最佳用途是在混合动力车中”。</p><p>我们的政策并不是为了激励碳减排，而是为了吸引富裕的美国人在他们的车库里腾出空间来放置超大的豪华电动汽车，这样特斯拉就可以报告利润，这样其他汽车制造商就可以在他们的“合规”汽车上蒙受更小的损失。遵守政府指令进行创建。</p><p>开采所需矿物会产生排放。保持电池充电会产生排放。只有大量汽油驾驶被取代，二氧化碳排放量才会净减少。但谁说汽油驾驶正在被取代呢？当政府为电动汽车提供税收减免时，当富裕的消费者挥霍购买一辆燃烧电子而不是汽油的汽车时，他们只是留下更多的汽油供其他人以更低的价格消费。</p><p>这对你们，公众来说可能是一个秘密。这不是经济学家的事。</p><p>在乔·拜登身上，</p>唉，我们的总统不像许多人那样能够区分听起来不错的事情和实际上做好的事情。媒体的情况也好不了多少。即使愿意承认政策的不合理性，它<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/14/opinion/electric-vehicles-toyota-hybrids.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">仍然</a>顽固地致力于将电动汽车视为美德信号。<p></p><p>电动汽车政策只满足政策可持续性的一项标准——它将消费者和纳税人的财富转移给特殊利益集团，从而诱骗选民支持。</p><p>这里的问题是任何补贴我们减排方式的计划的问题。如果价格合适，人类完全有能力消耗不断增长的可再生能源和污染能源。排放数据也证明了这一点。如何解释一路走来，气候空洞姿态与越来越多地高喊气候变化威胁人类生存这一毫无根据的主张的气候言论的共同演变？我这样解释：当很明显没有人会对气候变化采取任何行动时，就气候变化进行歇斯底里的言论就变得安全了。</p><p>在我职业生涯刚开始时，一位明智的导师谈到当时的新气候问题时说道：“那又怎样？”他的意思是他看不到人类放弃化石燃料。</p><p>我后来修改了这一点：通过将碳税纳入其税收体系，全球社会至少可以减缓二氧化碳排放速度，同时提高税法效率。这似乎仍然不太可能，但尚不清楚原因。毕竟，政客们征收了大量的税收。几十年来，政府一直被建议采用消费税作为为其福利国家提供资金的一种方式，同时又不破坏增长的可能性。</p><p>但我们到了。由于人类活动，大气的成分正在发生变化。计算地球的年平均温度可能与计算电话簿中的数字的平均值一样有意义。任何气候都可能发生不寻常的温暖、寒冷、潮湿或干燥天气。但只要宇宙是由物质和能量构成的，我们就应该预期大气中二氧化碳含量的改变会对地球产生一些影响。</p><p>一位也许是杜撰的爱德华时代政治家把他的报纸送到了地窖，他说，因为只有 20 年后才能清楚哪些新闻是重要的。请随意忽略每一个气候标题，直到有人说人类已开始向大气中注入硫酸盐颗粒以减少落在地球上的阳光量。只有这样，才会有人针对气候变化采取行动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=030EE4E1-084C-4369-AE30-4167FC65B664&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fof-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：进步政策促成了橙色烟雾风暴。图片：美联社/NurPhoto 来自 ZUMA Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d<category>碳税</category><category>排放量</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>气候变化</category><category>环境</category><category>范围</category><category>电池</category><category>地球</category><category>补贴</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>排放量</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境/社会/治理</category><category>空气污染</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>环境污染</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业环境责任</category><category>环境的</category><category>社会的</category><category>治理</category><category>空气污染</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>自然环境</category><category>环境污染</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Salsa in the Rain With Celia Cruz]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位流亡的古巴歌手于 2003 年去世。我参观了她的坟墓。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096082192814358"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590096082192814358"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">东姑·瓦拉达拉詹</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 18 日下午 6:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/salsa-celia-cruz-death-anniversary-fidel-castro-exile-cuba-communism-dance-music-protest-c84cc732"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819222?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">塞西莉亚·克鲁兹的坟墓。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：东姑·瓦拉达拉詹</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>纽约州布朗克斯</em></p><p>在我到达伍德劳恩公墓西莉亚·克鲁兹的坟墓几分钟后，天空将它们的内容倾倒在我们身上：一小群死忠粉丝挤在雨伞下。我们有十几个人，其中一半人穿着印有她脸的各种T恤。我特别想要一个，就问一个人在哪里买的。 “我自己做的，”他说。 “一个给我，一个给我的妻子。” He sounded almost rueful, as if he&#39;d let me down.</p><p> Sunday, July 16, was the 20th anniversary of the death of Úrsula Hilaria Celia de la Caridad Cruz Alfonso, known to the world as Celia Cruz. Feted as the queen of salsa, she was the most melodious exile from Fidel Castro&#39;s Cuba—and among the most unyielding. An obituary at the time of her death noted that she&#39;d made peace with the knowledge that she would die in the US, not in her beloved Cuba. In 2000, she recorded a song, “ <em>Por si acaso no regreso</em> ”—in case I don&#39;t return—the forlorn but unbowed lamentation of a Cuban patriot who senses that her exile will outlive her.</p><p> Castro declared her persona non grata in 1960, a year after his revolution. She was 35 and had traveled to Mexico to fulfill some recording contracts. She chose to make her home in New York and later New Jersey. Celia was hostile to Castro, fiercely anticommunist, and had turned down a request to sing his favorite song at a concert in Havana. The vengeful <em>comandante</em> didn&#39;t let her return for her mother&#39;s funeral in 1962. Thirty years after she left Cuba, she performed at the US naval base at Guantanamo Bay, the only time she set foot on the island after the ban on her return. She took a fistful of soil with her from Guantanamo, which was entombed with her at Woodlawn.</p><p> On Sunday, the cemetery threw open the doors to her tomb, where her husband, Pedro Knight, lies alongside her. A spokesman for the cemetery, present there in the rain, told me hers is “the most-visited burial site” at Woodlawn—which is remarkable for a woman who didn&#39;t sing a word of English and, notwithstanding her love for America, lived only for the day she could return to Cuba. Remarkable, also, when you consider the competition at the cemetery: Herman Melville, Thomas Nast, Dorothy Parker, Duke Ellington, Miles Davis, Irving Berlin, Fiorello LaGuardia, Joseph Pulitzer.</p><p> America embraced Celia Cruz. Yale conferred on her an honorary doctorate in 1989—along with Stephen Hawking, Isaiah Berlin and Justice Lewis Powell. In 1994 Bill Clinton awarded her the President&#39;s Award for the National Endowment for the Arts.</p><p> As we stood in the rain, someone played some Celia on his iPhone, her rich contralto defying the acoustic limits of a tinny speaker. “ <em>Soy de la Cuba de ayer</em> ,” she sang—I am from the Cuba of yesterday, a prelapsarian place before Castro&#39;s coming.</p><p> And then, shortly after, the tomb was closed. It will open to the public again in 10 years. Perhaps Cuba will be free by then.</p><p> <em>Mr. Varadarajan, a Journal contributor, is a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute and at New York University Law School&#39;s Classical Liberal Institute.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B89B2690-0317-40F9-A22B-4C9D280DCCCC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsalsa-celia-cruz-death-anniversary-fidel-castro-exile-cuba-communism-dance-music-protest-c84cc732&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady) 和丹·亨宁格 (Dan Henninger) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片来源：美联社/EPA/Shutterstock/Reuters/Zuma Press 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salsa-celia-cruz-death-anniversary-fidel-castro-exile-cuba-communism-dance-music-protest-c84cc732</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salsa-celia-cruz-death-anniversary-fidel-castro-exile-cuba-communism-dance-music-protest-c84cc732<category> cuba</category><category> havana</category><category> communism</category><category> totalitarianism</category><category> free speech</category><category> exile</category><category> art</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>音乐</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Louis Armstrong Center Review: Jazz’s King in Queens]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The center, which opened across from the Louis Armstrong House Museum, preserves the trumpeter&#39;s legacy with a performance space and a permanent 60,000-item archive of personal items. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094183848430758"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819456?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Louis Armstrong Center</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Albert Vecerka/Esto </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094183848430758"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Larry Blumenfeld</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 6:24 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-louis-armstrong-center-review-jazzs-king-in-queens-cac8057c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Corona, NY</em></p><p> In 1943, Louis Armstrong returned to New York from a performance tour. His wife, Lucille, had instructed him to take a taxi to 34-56 107th Street, in Corona, Queens. This modest, two-story brick-façade house on a quiet, tree-lined street was now their home; Lucille had purchased it.</p><p> The famed trumpeter, who lived there until his death in 1971, at 69 years old, became part of the fabric of this community—“a regular, just like anyone else,” said one neighbor in a documentary, and, as Lucille described in interviews, “a pied piper” to the block&#39;s children.</p><p> The Louis Armstrong House Museum opened its doors in 2003, under the auspices of Queens College, City University of New York, looking much as the Armstrongs left it. The trumpeter&#39;s life here was documented with rare dedication. Ricky Riccardi, the museum&#39;s director of research collections and the author of two Armstrong books, told me: “Armstrong knew that one day they were going to write about him in history books. He wanted to make sure all sides of him—good, bad, ugly—were going to be captured and preserved, by himself.” Armstrong&#39;s reel-to-reel tapes contain not just music but also personal ruminations and casual conversations with his friends, famous and not; excerpts can be triggered by buttons positioned around the house.</p><p> That material barely hints at the 60,000 items in the Louis Armstrong Archive, established under the stewardship of Michael Cogswell at Queens College in 1991. Cogswell, who died in 2020, had long envisioned a companion center for the full collection, the world&#39;s largest for any single jazz musician. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819452?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Chris Barham photograph of Louis Armstrong with children outside his home in Queens</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: LOUIS ARMSTRONG HOUSE MUSEUM</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Now it is a reality. The $26 million, 14,000-square-foot Louis Armstrong Center, which opened July 6 across the street from the House Museum and was designed by Caples Jefferson Architects, looks thoroughly modern—its undulations suggest a grand piano&#39;s shape—yet it honors the street&#39;s two-story roofline. It stands out and fits in, just like Armstrong did. At a ribbon-cutting ceremony, a dozen notable trumpeters played the opening cadenzas from Armstrong&#39;s 1928 recording of “West End Blues” (still American music&#39;s most revolutionary 15 seconds).</p><p> Regina Bain, the House Museum&#39;s executive director, called the Center a “physical manifestation and interpretation” of Louis and Lucille&#39;s lives and legacies, best honored “by telling their stories, and by living their values.” Speaking from the podium, Angel Toledo and Eddie Garcia, third-grade classmates who now live on the block, extended a legacy of the children who surrounded Armstrong on his stoop in Chris Barham&#39;s classic 1970 photographs. At the podium, Angel, struck by the story of a proud and uncompromising black artist who spoke his mind, compared Armstrong to Martin Luther King Jr. ; Armstrong&#39;s example, Eddie said, inspired him to study music. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="505" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819450?width=700&amp;height=505" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Installation view of &#39;Here to Stay&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Albert Vecerka/Esto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Inside the Center&#39;s 75-seat venue, a jazz ensemble from Queens&#39;s Frank Sinatra School of the Arts High School played standards. Nearby, in the inaugural exhibition, “Here to Stay,” curated by jazz pianist Jason Moran, were Armstrong&#39;s first passport, from 1932, and his last one, circa 1967. Cylindrical display cases and interactive kiosks tell the remarkable story—simultaneously humble and exceptional—in between: the Selmer trumpet and mouthpiece given to Armstrong by King George V of England; the trumpeter&#39;s six-page, handwritten ode to Corona, titled “Our Neighborhood.” Video narrations at kiosks, by Mr. Moran and Ms. Bain, feature passages from the books in Armstrong&#39;s home library, including the 1951 “Homemakers&#39; Idea Book” and 1973&#39;s “The Black Book,” compiled by Toni Morrison as an investigation of the black experience in America.</p><p> “Let&#39;s look at what Louis saved,” Mr. Moran said of his curatorial process, “to find language for how vast his personality was, and how complex were the situations he navigated while making music.” Mr. Moran, whose own visual art has been exhibited at the Whitney Museum of American Art, was fascinated by Armstrong&#39;s collages—hundreds, mostly adorning reel-to-reel tape boxes, some of which are on view. Reel 58&#39;s cover is dominated by a lovely photo of Lucille, with barely perceptible cutouts of Louis and his trumpet cropped into her likeness. Others turn press clippings from tours, private photographs, found art and handwritten notes into highly personalized swirls of images and text. The effects are, by turns, touching, funny and mesmerizing.</p><p> In a video, Mr. Moran compares Armstrong&#39;s own description of his cut-and-paste art strategy to his music—“Armstrong could also be explaining his process as a trumpeter, finding the right melodic nugget in a song, exaggerating the phrase to make it stand out in relief from the band.” He marvels at Armstrong&#39;s “ability to synthesize an extravagant life into a humble square.”</p><p> The Armstrong House reveals precisely where and how Louis Armstrong lived. Across the street, the 54 artifacts and hundreds of digitized images in the Center&#39;s inaugural exhibition—most of which will be permanent, all of which are lovingly arranged and lend thoughtful context—deepen our understanding of who the trumpeter was: a gregarious entertainer yet also an introspective artist; a performer on the road 300 days a year who adored his Queens neighborhood; a well-read seeker whose smile could mean many things.</p><p> And it makes a larger point. Jazz often lives and grows in residential spaces far from celebrated venues. Protecting these spots, building upon them, keeps the spirits of singular inspirations alive where they might otherwise be paved over or forgotten. Such acts reinforce jazz as a culture marked by individuals, families and communities, each with their own story.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Blumenfeld writes about jazz and Afro-Latin music for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-louis-armstrong-center-review-jazzs-king-in-queens-cac8057c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-louis-armstrong-center-review-jazzs-king-in-queens-cac8057c<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Tao of the Backup Catcher’ Review: Roughing It on the Diamond]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Baseball&#39;s ultimate journeymen survive by exhibiting a level of humility we would never expect of everyday players. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12099543776899034024404590069981831281898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819083?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> David Ross of the Boston Red Sox in 2014.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rob Carr/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12099543776899034024404590069981831281898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Alva Noë</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 6:23 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tao-of-the-backup-catcher-review-roughing-it-on-the-diamond-3f9dfd1e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Baseball is a sport in hiding. The media celebrates the big hit, the virtuosic defensive play and the strikeout, but so much of the real action comes between all that. What pitch should we throw, now, to <em>this</em> hitter? It depends on who the hitter is but also on the pitcher&#39;s arsenal, the count, the score and the situation on the bases. Not to mention whether the pitcher is tired or has his best stuff.</p><p> The catcher is the hidden center of this quietly unfolding drama. We attend, naturally, to the pitcher, standing tall on the mound. It&#39;s easy to miss his accomplice, crouching behind the batter. To reliably handle the pitch, the catcher must know what&#39;s coming, and that means the duo must be of one mind. They need a private language—one the batter doesn&#39;t speak—that lets them operate as a true battery.</p><p> Tim Brown&#39;s “The Tao of the Backup Catcher” reveals another hidden dimension of baseball. I don&#39;t think I&#39;ll ever view the game the same way after reading this book, written with the longtime backup catcher Erik Kratz. Mr. Brown, a veteran baseball writer, describes the grind of the comparatively mediocre players whose jobs are always in doubt and who bounce from team to team, frequently at the minor-league level. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/2d983332-9f23-4a3b-919f-b0bff3bace50.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Kratz, who survived at the fringes of the majors before a star turn for the Milwaukee Brewers during the 2018 playoffs, is a paradigm case. As Mr. Brown writes, Kratz played 19 seasons for 14 organizations. His career included stints with “sixteen different minor league teams, along with one Arizona Fall League team, one Dominican Winter league team, two US national teams, a team in Mexico, and one alternate site team” during the pandemic. Such longevity requires grit, dedication and the ability to perform whenever and wherever the opportunity arises.</p><p> The catcher&#39;s job is grueling. Playing a whole game means coming out of the crouch and throwing balls back to the mound more than 100 times. The bruises from foul balls off the neck, the demands of guiding your pitching staff, the burdens placed on you as a hitter and baserunner: all take a toll. If you are a No. 1 catcher, you need days off. So you need a backup who can play a couple times a week, and also be ready to substitute at a moment&#39;s notice due to injury. More importantly, you need someone without pretensions to stardom.</p><p> Mr. Brown explores how some catchers come to accept the role of backup. Take the case of David Ross, now the manager of the Chicago Cubs. Ross only became an excellent backup after he gave up his aspiration to be a starter. The author points to a candid conversation that Ross had in 2008 with Theo Epstein, then an executive with the Boston Red Sox. Mr. Epstein convinced the frustrated Ross of his value if he could “reinvent himself and let go of the things he can&#39;t control and just focus on the team.” As a committed backup, Ross became a beloved teammate and a winning player, a World Series champion with the Red Sox in 2013 and the Cubs in 2016.</p><p> Playing the role of backup, at catcher or any other position, often means worrying about being cut or demoted. A backup usually fields the position well, but if he hits and runs relatively poorly he will be considered, in effect, expendable. There&#39;s always another player with marginal skills out there looking for a job. To survive, the backup needs to add value to the position. It&#39;s a bit of a paradox: The backup, who is by definition not up to par, needs to make himself indispensable.</p><p> There are many ways for catchers to do this. Some backups secure their position through specialization—they learn to catch the knuckleball, or get paired with particular pitchers. Eddie Pérez of the Atlanta Braves, for example, was the personal catcher of the Hall of Fame pitcher Greg Maddux. Others, Mr Brown suggests, cultivate leadership qualities. It&#39;s no coincidence that so many catchers, like Ross, later become managers.</p><p> Consider Matt Treanor, one of many catchers struggling for a roster spot at the Kansas City Royals&#39; spring training camp in 1997. He was using his favorite, tried-and-true mitt in a bullpen session with an aging pitcher who was anxious about his reduced velocity. The pitcher, rather obnoxiously, demanded that Treanor get a new glove; he warned him not to show up with that old mitt again.</p><p> Treanor didn&#39;t get angry. He understood that the pitcher was needy and wanted to hear the pop of his fastball against new leather. He appreciated that one of his job requirements was to do everything necessary to keep the pitcher in the saddle. That&#39;s the special value required of a secondary catcher.</p><p> To survive as a backup, you have to exhibit a degree of humility and selflessness that you would neither need nor be able to cultivate if you were an everyday catcher. Mr. Brown puts it like this in the book&#39;s opening lines: “If you will work your whole young life to become strong and clever, to see the game in ways others don&#39;t or can&#39;t, if you will commit wholly to yourself, the group, the win, and today, and if you then will give it all away, then you will be the backup catcher.”</p><p> This is a subordinate, unglamorous but deeply valuable baseball existence. Indeed, as the stories that fill this book suggest, baseball aside, it is a valuable kind of life.</p><p> <em>Mr. Noë is the author of “Infinite Baseball: Notes From a Philosopher at the Ballpark” and “The Entanglement: How Art and Philosophy Make Us What We Are.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tao-of-the-backup-catcher-review-roughing-it-on-the-diamond-3f9dfd1e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-tao-of-the-backup-catcher-review-roughing-it-on-the-diamond-3f9dfd1e<category>棒球</category><category>Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>baseball</category><category> books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Black Sands’ Review: Perilous Prospects, Nordic Noir]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In a bingeable Icelandic series on Viaplay, a detective returns to her tight-knit hometown and helps a refreshingly human police force with a murder investigation. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094072204487394"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818595?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Aldís Amah Hamilton</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Viaplay </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590094072204487394"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">John Anderson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 6:17 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sands-review-perilous-prospects-nordic-noir-b39e9aa8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> When the term <em>film noir</em> was coined in the 1940s, it signified melodramas defined by black-and-white imagery and morality cast in shades of gray: Few villains were all bad; few heroes were all good. And few settings are grayer, visually or otherwise, than the Icelandic shorefront captured in the Nordic noir series “Black Sands,” a frosty take on the oft-warmed-over police procedural. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Black Sands</strong></p><p><strong></strong> <em>Thursday, Viaplay</em></p></div></div><p> Remote even by Icelandic standards, the small town at the center of director Baldvin Z&#39;s dramatic series is rocked one morning when the body of a young woman is found on the volcanic beach, having plummeted from a scenic overlook a few hundred feet above. Those left behind will be falling through their own cosmic space over eight episodes, but they shouldn&#39;t be surprised by the dead girl: Their area has had an inordinately high rate of “accidents” in recent years, considering the size of the jurisdiction. No one has put all the pieces together, and won&#39;t for several episodes. But one of the more refreshing things about “Black Sands” is that no one on the police force is an investigative genius. The department is barely professional. They don&#39;t even act their age.</p><p> But this gives the storyline credibility and even calls into question the modus operandi of the standard mystery series: Would police officers think about nothing but the case that they—and we—are concerned with at a given time? No, they wouldn&#39;t. If he or she were Aníta (the arresting Aldís Amah Hamilton ), her thoughts might be on the married lover she&#39;s just left behind in Reykjavík, who won&#39;t leave his wife and has sent her home with “her tail between her legs,” as described by her unsympathetic mother, Elin (Steinunn Ólína Þorsteinsdóttir). That lover will be occupying her mind when she gets a call from her colleague Raggi (Þór Tulinius), saying there&#39;s been a body found and can she help him out? When she gets to the beach, and the body half sunk in the sand, she and her fellow officers—and the local doctor-coroner Salómon (Kolbeinn Arnbjörnsson)—will catch up, talk about everything but the accident victim (if that&#39;s what she is), joke, laugh and go about their police business. It may seem disrespectful of the dead, but it doesn&#39;t feel the least bit false. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818597?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ms. Hamilton and Þór Tulinius</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Viaplay </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Television Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/superpowered-the-dc-story-review-max-imum-glorification-7d98deb0?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Superpowered: The DC Story&#39; Review: Max(imum) Glorification</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/goliath-review-how-wilt-chamberlain-changed-the-game-518350d4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Goliath&#39; Review: How Wilt Chamberlain Changed the Game</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-house-made-of-splinters-review-mending-broken-souls-in-ukraine-79d31639?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;A House Made of Splinters&#39; Review: Mending Broken Souls in Ukraine</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/emmy-awards-2023-wsjs-tv-critic-on-this-years-nominees-airdigital-a6cba6f5?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Emmy Awards 2023: WSJ&#39;s TV Critic on This Year&#39;s Nominees</a> <span class="date">July 12, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Neither does the measured pace of the unfolding mystery. Why would anyone suspect foul play? Well, because a second woman has been attacked, too, but, clinging to the cliff, she&#39;s managed to survive. Or so she says. As becomes clear, the innocence, or naiveté, of the locale makes it a perfect place for murder. The tiresome tourists—whom all the townsfolk complain about—are perfect victims. But when the police make mistakes, as they inevitably will under such circumstances, those errors—born of inexperience, or fatigue, or hangovers, or presumptions—will come back to haunt them.</p><p> Ms. Hamilton, a co-writer of the series (and of its second season, now in production), has been honored at home for her performance, and the series has been nominated for a number of Edda Awards (the Icelandic Oscar, so to speak). The cast overall is first-rate and the small dramas are numerous, and involving enough, to make “Black Sands” a bingeable excursion northward, into an atmosphere that seems naturally noirish.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Anderson is the Journal&#39;s TV critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sands-review-perilous-prospects-nordic-noir-b39e9aa8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sands-review-perilous-prospects-nordic-noir-b39e9aa8<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Superpowered: The DC Story’ Review: Max(imum) Glorification]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A three-episode documentary on the far-from-disinterested Max trumpets the journey of heroes like Superman and Batman from comic books to the films and shows of Warner Bros. Discovery. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093920462758754"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818619?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Robert Pattinson, one of the many actors that have played Batman</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Warner Bros. Discovery </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093920462758754"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">John Anderson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 18, 2023 6:14 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/superpowered-the-dc-story-review-max-imum-glorification-7d98deb0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In the arena of globe-straddling entertainment conglomerates, “superpowered” means owning a movie studio, a publishing company, multiple streaming outlets, a decades-long back catalog and a bottomless well of human talent and technology; “chutzpah” means using all those elements to make a three-hour advertisement for yourself. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Superpowered: The DC Story</strong></p><p><strong></strong> <em>Thursday, Max</em></p></div></div><p> “Superpowered: The DC Story,” which celebrates the comic-book company specifically and Warner Bros. Discovery generally (and is appearing on the WBD outlet Max), is hardly without precedent in an industry devoted to self-love; Disney and its subsidiary Marvel, for instance, regularly recycle their properties, plotlines and copyrights. In May, wanting to get in the same self-aggrandizing groove, Warner Bros. Discovery presented “100 Years of Warner Bros.,” which availed itself of the studio&#39;s fat film library, employed a few convenient sins of historical omission and spent two hours glorifying the brand. Likewise, the three-part “Superpowered” tells the origin story of DC Comics—superheroes love origin stories—but inevitably wanders into film, television and the evolution of the DC worldview.</p><p> It celebrates the little guys: Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster, the under-compensated creators of Superman; Bill Finger, Bob Kane&#39;s acknowledged, impoverished collaborator in the creation of Batman; and dozens of others who never quite got their due or their money. That “Superpowered” is making its debut during the writers-actors strike may qualify as double chutzpah, but it is probably just an accident of bad timing and worse optics.</p><p> It isn&#39;t a boring show, though the amount of blather generated in an effort to deify DC and its now-parent company is excessive, embarrassing, and sometimes bewilderingly both. By the end of the &#39;60s, for instance, after several decades of great success, the superhero comic book had basically crash-landed. “If America could land a man on the moon,” someone says, “how hard could it be to make superheroes relevant again?” Did she really say that? Are superheroes “icons of virtue” or “symbols of our greatest ideals” to whom we are drawn because “something in our moral compass” brings us to them? Well, maybe. But the effort to make comic books and their television and movie adaptations “important,” or claim that a graphic novel belongs among the ranks of the world&#39;s greatest literature, isn&#39;t an argument that should be made so seriously, if one wants to be taken seriously. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Television Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sands-review-perilous-prospects-nordic-noir-b39e9aa8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Black Sands&#39; Review: Perilous Prospects, Nordic Noir</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/goliath-review-how-wilt-chamberlain-changed-the-game-518350d4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Goliath&#39; Review: How Wilt Chamberlain Changed the Game</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-house-made-of-splinters-review-mending-broken-souls-in-ukraine-79d31639?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;A House Made of Splinters&#39; Review: Mending Broken Souls in Ukraine</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/emmy-awards-2023-wsjs-tv-critic-on-this-years-nominees-airdigital-a6cba6f5?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Emmy Awards 2023: WSJ&#39;s TV Critic on This Year&#39;s Nominees</a> <span class="date">July 12, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Celebrating the comic-book birthplace of Superman, Batman, Wonder Woman, etc., “Superpowered” wheels through various stories familiar and not—the 1938 debut of Action Comics, which introduced Superman; the 1978 production of “Superman: The Movie,” which resuscitated the entire medium. The rivalry between DC and Marvel consumes a large part of the storyline, and the series, unlike most of this ilk, improves from episode 1 to 2 because it gets into the philosophy of comic books, the tension that exists between comics and graphic novels being vehicles for pure fantasy vs. focusing them—or, in DC&#39;s case, reorienting them—to reflect current events and cultural change. That some of the voices in “Superpowered” are still indignant about the campy treatment of “Batman” in the hit ABC series of 1966 is typical of the overly sober regard with which many of the interviewees hold their characters and storylines. Which is a lot funnier than most of the new series ought to have been.</p><p> Given the apparent difficulties being faced by both the small screen and the cinema, “Superpowered” and its navel-gazing, insulated approach to entertainment marks something troubling about current film and TV in general—a painful contraction of the creative landscape and a shameless expansion of marketing into the public head space. Hollywood product has long been about selling other products, whether it means things that actually appear on screen or the worldview perpetrated by the stories. Given its checkered record so far and the self-inflicted wounds it has caused to its brand (by the killing of “Batgirl,” for example, or its demonstrated disregard for the beloved Turner Classic Movies), Warner Bros. Discovery, with “Superpowered,” continues not to do itself any favors.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Anderson is the Journal&#39;s TV critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 22:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/superpowered-the-dc-story-review-max-imum-glorification-7d98deb0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/superpowered-the-dc-story-review-max-imum-glorification-7d98deb0<category>艺术评论</category><category>广播</category><category>Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Movies</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><categ